Every patch of World of Warcraft releases a new raid tier and season. Each expansion contains a range of dungeons that 5 people will go in and attempt to complete. There have been varying difficulties over the years, but more recently, it has been toned to normal, heroic, and mythic difficulties, with mythic containing a trial mode based on an affix and key system. Each dungeon group contains a tank, a healer, and 3 damage dealers. The focus of this document is to analyze damage dealer class performance and representation, and possible attempt to identify which types of classes have a history of success to determine which classes to play going into the new expansion: Dragonflight.

To start, let's look at the most recent season in the 9.2 patch of the expansion: Shadowlands. To do so, we have a number of options. Raider.io is a website that pulls from the warcraft api to compile comprehensive leader boards for raid and dungeon rankings. Warcraftlogs is another site that takes in user generate combat logs and completes statistical analysis on individual and class performance, but Warcraftlogs is primarily for raid encounters.

From raider.io we can pull each classes' spec performers over the 9.2 mythic dungeon season patch. The Score associated with each player is calculated based on the highest level completion (with a bonus to competions within the time limit) across all dungeons in the expansion. Each dungeon carries a high score, and the total player score value is aggregated across all available dungeons. In short, a higher score means higher average difficulty dungeon competions. From this report, we can upload the information into a CSV that is available in the github repository supporting this webpage. For access to the original data, please visit https://raider.io/.

To expand a bit more on the key system, after a dungeon is completed, a key to a random dungeon is dropped for all members. This key increases the difficulty of the next dungeon, scaling infinitely. Rewards are capped at +15, but the score reward is uncapped. Groups will try to push higher keys in an attempt to gain more score for the leaderboards.

The data stored within the following table contains the top 10 players for each dps specialization for each class.

Before moving into the history of each class over the expansion, we have yet to address another major component within the data set. One of the key selling features of the Shadowlands expansion for World of Warcraft was the Covenant system. Each player selects a faction (covenant) to join, and along with cosmetic rewards, they gain two additional abilties. One is covenant specific, and the other is class and covenant specific. The consequence of this, many players imagined, would be that high end players would be forced to select the "best" covenant in terms of player power instead of the covenant that felt was the most interesting. The data from the raider.io contains covenant information for the top performers along with their scores. Let's take another look:

Clearly, only a few classes have any covenant diversity. Paladins and Monks only use one covenant, and for most specs, one covenant is a clear winner in popularity. In 9.0, the launch of Shadowlands, swapping covenants not only reset all progress in terms of power progression, but swapping back to a covenant one has left was time gated behind a two week waiting period. I would like to highlight the failure of the system in regards to allowing players to choose freely, indicating an imaginary balance between covenants for each class, but the mandated friction only compounds the issue of covenant imbalance.

Speaking of imbalance, let's focus back on dungeon performance across Shadowland's history. When choosing a class to play, most players end up playing one or two classes at most. This changes by season and expansion, but the ease of creating a new character varies, so the initial choice of what to play at the start does matter, so how did classes perform over the course of the expansion? Were players able to at some point feel value in their decision?

The first factor of note is that the scale of IO score is less in 9.0 than in 9.2. This would be due to player power creep over the course of the expansion, with player strength scaling exponentially, meaning higher keys are able to be completed in the later season compared to the launch season. However, when looking at class and spec performance by relation, we can see a number of different trends in the difference of season. Certain specs, such as Fire mage and Sub rouge, have very different performances compared to their peers in the different patches. Fire was very successful in 9.0, and Sub was as well in 9.2, but in the opposite patches the specs fell off. Let's compare all the spec performances, accounting for the difference in mean score through standardizing across a patch.

In [58]:
mean90 = Dungeon90Ranks.Score.mean()
std90 = Dungeon90Ranks.Score.std()

temp90 = Dungeon90Ranks.groupby(['Spec']).mean()
temp90.reset_index(inplace=True)
temp90.drop(columns=['Rank'])

for index, row in temp90.iterrows():
    temp90.at[index, 'Score'] = (temp90.at[index, 'Score'] - mean90) / std90

This new plot is able to show relative spec IO performance over the entire expansion, from 9.0 to 9.2. People who chose outlaw clearly got the short end of the stick, where once a top performing spec is now bottom tier in 9.2. This data does require looking at initial spec performance, because one would believe affliction to be in a similar state as outlaw, but in truth, affliction was never top tier to begin with, yet was never buffed in compensation. Balance also seems to have fall off hard, just as outlaw, but again this is misleading. In reality, balance was so extremely ahead in 9.0, that in 9.2, it is actually quite average, yet the standardization would have one think it was terrible. I imagine players who chose warlock and wanted to play Affliction, like myself, feel neglected by the game's balance team.

With all the knowledge we now have, the big question left is "Should I play melee or ranged dps in the new WoW expansion: Dragonflight?"

While of course everything here will be speculation, we can use past trends to find the specs that have a history of success over the course of expansions. Dungeons so far have always had "trash," which are enemies to kill in area of effect damage, and dungeons always have bosses with their own mechanics. Based on past performance over many dungeons and seasons, we can hope to predict some top classes that always find their way into the meta. The choice of melee or ranged can be used as a guide for developing a dungeon team composition, so this initial choice will end up being important for competitive groups.

Going into this experiment, we can state a null hypothesis of H0: Melee-Range = 0, or in comprehensible terms, there is no significant difference between melee and ranged.
